      "title": "London’s most notorious thief was also a hero of the people",
      "content": "<p><strong>A</strong> Jack Sheppard, an expert in lock-picking, gained notoriety in the 18th century for his remarkable escapes from London's prisons. Despite his fame, the stringent English laws against theft ultimately led to his execution.</p><p><strong>B</strong> On November 16, 1724, a crowd of 200,000 gathered at Tyburn, London, to witness the execution of 21-year-old John “Jack” Sheppard. Once a carpenter’s apprentice, Sheppard became a well-known figure in 18th-century England due to his daring prison escapes, which occurred during a period when the British working class faced an increasingly harsh criminal justice system.</p><p><strong>C</strong> Born in 1702 in Spitalfields, East London, Sheppard came from a modest family of carpenters. After his father's death, his mother raised him and his siblings alone. Sheppard followed in his father's footsteps, becoming a carpenter's apprentice. Despite his small stature, he was robust and skilled with locks. His penchant for luxury led him into a life of petty theft, a path he was already on before meeting Elizabeth Lyon, known as Edgeworth Bess, who allegedly influenced his criminal activities.</p><p><strong>D</strong> Sheppard's descent into crime was not unique. The unregulated commercial and colonial expansion in Britain marginalized many working-class individuals, leading to a rise in thievery and banditry. Figures like highwayman Dick Turpin and gangster Jonathan Wild became infamous, with Wild amassing wealth through organized crime while betraying fellow criminals to authorities.</p><p><strong>E</strong> In early 18th-century England, property crimes were severely punished, often more so than crimes against individuals. The rise of the bourgeoisie made property protection a state priority, resulting in harsh penalties, including death sentences, for theft.</p><p><strong>F</strong> Unlike other criminals, Sheppard did not resort to violence. His non-violent methods and choice of targets contributed to his status as a folk hero. He focused on the bourgeoisie, using his agility and lock-picking skills to commit small-scale thefts from their homes.</p><p><strong>G</strong> Sheppard's eventual imprisonment was due to betrayal rather than police work. His brother Thomas and friend James Sykes turned him in for personal gain. In 1724, Sheppard was arrested five times, escaping all but the last, which cemented his fame.</p><p><strong>H</strong> Sheppard's third escape from Newgate prison, aided by a disguise and distraction, elevated him to legendary status. Newspapers portrayed him as a folk hero, and a reward was offered for his capture. Despite being recaptured and placed in Newgate's most secure room, Sheppard escaped again, showcasing his determination and skill.</p><p><strong>I</strong> After his final escape, Sheppard resumed his criminal activities, leading to his recognition and arrest. This time, he was heavily guarded until his execution on November 16, 1724, which drew significant public attention.</p><p><strong>J</strong> Sheppard's execution was notable for its large audience and his demeanor, which included joking with guards. His reputation as a working-class hero persisted, with many viewing his crimes as victimless and his defiance of the judicial system as admirable.</p><p><strong>K</strong> Posthumously, Sheppard's reputation was further shaped by publications like his supposed autobiography, likely ghostwritten by Daniel Defoe, which portrayed him positively.</p><p><strong>L</strong> Sheppard's romanticized image continued to grow, with works like John Gay's The Beggar’s Opera and William Harrison Ainsworth's novel Jack Sheppard: A Romance, which depicted him as a symbol of rebellion against societal inequality.</p>",
